  <title lang="en">Anonymity</title>
  <summary lang="en">Application of <i>Anonymization</i> </summary>
  <description lang="en">Shows the application of anonymization methods to datasets</description>
  <keywords>anonymization, k-Anonymity, l-Diversity, t-Closeness</keywords>
  <replacements lang="en">
  <replacement key="$textinput$" value="Input data" />
  <replacement key="$dataset$" value="Name,Gender,Postal Code,Diagnosis&#10;John,male,68169,Flu&#10;Max,male,62317,Cancer&#10;George,male,64623,Depression&#10;Hans,male,65324,Cancer&#10;Sabine,female,49632,Cold&#10;Clara,female,47123,Flu&#10;Michelle,female,41339,Cancer&#10;Sarah,female,47965,Flu" />
  <replacement key="$anonymity$" value="Anonymity" />
  <replacement key="$textoutput$" value="Anonymized output data" />
  <replacement key="$memo$" value="The {\b Anonymity Component} allows the application of anonymization methods such as k-Anonymity, l-Diversity (Distinct l-Diversity, Entropy l-Diversity, Recursive (c,l)-Diversity) and t-Closeness to a CSV-based dataset.\line
\line
{\b k-Anonymity:} This technique protects privacy by ensuring that the data of each individual in a publication cannot be distinguished from those of at least k−1 other individuals. This is often achieved through generalization or suppression of data sets.\line
\line
{\b l-Diversity (Distinct l-Diversity):} Extends k-Anonymity by requiring that there be at least l different sensitive values in each group of k-anonymous data. This helps prevent attacks such as homogeneity and background knowledge.\line
\line
{\b l-Diversity (Entropy l-Diversity):} A variation of l-Diversity, where the entropy of the sensitive data in a group is considered. It aims to ensure sufficient &quot;disorder&quot; to complicate the prediction of sensitive data.\line
\line
{\b l-Diversity (Recursive (c,l)-Diversity):} This form improves l-Diversity by considering the difference in the number of the most and least common sensitive values and ensures that this difference stays within certain limits (defined by c and l).\line
\line
{\b t-Closeness:} This method further refines k-Anonymity by demanding that the distribution of sensitive attributes in each anonymized group deviates no more than a threshold t from the distribution of the entire dataset, thus complicating the use of background information to uncover sensitive data." />\line
  </replacements>
